> Vinegar, soy sauce, ginger, and honey combine for a ridiculously easy and
> incredibly flavorful sweet-and-sour glaze. It's meant to coat the chicken,
> but we have a feeling you'll be sneaking some on the rice and crispy snap
> peas as well.

Cook the rice: Bring @water{1%cup} and a pinch of @salt{pinch} to a boil in a
#small pot{}. Once boiling, add the @Jasmine Rice{1/2%cup}. Cover and reduce
to a low simmer for ~{15-20%minutes}, until tender.

Wash and dry all produce. Cut the @Lime{1} into wedges. Peel the
@Ginger{1%thumb}, then mince enough to make 2 Tablespoons. Mince or grate the
@Garlic{2%cloves}. Trim the ends of the @Sugar Snap Peas{6%ounce}.

Season the @Chicken Breasts{12%ounce} on all sides with @Salt{pinch} and
@Pepper{pinch}. Heat a drizzle of @Olive Oil{1%tablespoon} in a #large pan{}
over medium-high heat. Add the chicken. Cook ~{4-5%minutes} per side, until
browned and cooked through. Remove from the pan and set aside. Wipe out any
black bits from the pan.

Heat a drizzle of oil in the same pan over medium heat. Add 2 Tablespoons
ginger and the garlic. Cook, tossing, for ~{2-3%minutes}, until soft and
fragrant. Add 1½ Tablespoons @White Wine Vinegar{2%tablespoon}(we sent more),
and let it reduce until the vinegar is nearly evaporated. Add the
@Chicken Stock Concentrate{1}, @Honey{1%jar}, 1 Tablespoon @Soy Sauce{3%teaspoon},
and 2 Tablespoons @water{2%tablespoon}. Reduce to a low simmer. Cook until
thickened to a glaze-like consistency, ~{2-3%minutes}. Remove pan from heat.

Return the chicken to the pan, and turn to thoroughly coat in the glaze. Heat a
drizzle of oil in a #medium pan{} over medium heat. Add the snap peas. Cook,
tossing, for ~{3-4%minutes}, until crisp-tender. Season with salt and pepper.

Plate: Serve the honey-and-ginger-glazed chicken and snap peas on a bed of
jasmine rice with lime wedges for squeezing. Enjoy!